	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p>A widow&#33; what a world of sorrow<lb/> and care is comprised in that epithet&#44;<lb/> if young&#44; he of whom she is bereaved<lb/> was yet the object of those warm and<lb/> gushing affections whose light was the<lb/> bright dream of her maidenhood&#44; and<lb/> if of maturer age&#44; years of companionship<lb/> had <add>&#63;</add> those ardent feelings only to<lb/> purify <del>them</del> them&#59; the hours of calm<lb/> converse&#44; the plans <del>the</del> hopes&#44; wishes of<lb/><sic>of</sic> which their children were the theme&#44;<lb/> all have served to deepen the love<lb/> that in the early season of their wedded<lb/> life seemed incapable of greater intensity&#59;<lb/> and now at none she weeps alone&#44; in<lb/> the first anguish of bereavement what can<lb/> console her. Has she ceased to love her<lb/> children&#44; no no but in looking on them<lb/> she only thinks alas he is no longer here<lb/> to watch with me their growing loveli&#45;<lb/>ness&#44; to check their wayward deed or<lb/> train to better thought.  But now there<lb/> comes a holy calm&#44; whence is it&#63; see</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>the Book of Books it lies before her &#8220;A<lb/> Husband to the Widow&#44; A Father to the<lb/> Fatherless.&#8221;  This gracious promise&#44; the<lb/> sacred injunction defraud not nor<lb/> oppress them&#59; yes thus she finds her<lb/> bitter grief allayed&#44; the children whom<lb/> God himself makes object of especial<lb/> love&#44; shall she not strive to lead them<lb/> to Him&#44; shall she not seek with earnest<lb/> prayer and trusting hope His guidance<lb/> in that holiest task a mothers training<lb/> of her offspring&#44; and in grateful reliance<lb/> say He who has stricken can console.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">To the <addressee>Rev I Leeser</addressee></p>
				<p>That in our small community&#44; three<lb/> bereavements of the kind alluded to has<lb/> occurred in that many weeks&#44; led to to the<lb/> train of thought that if you <add>&#63;</add> please dear<lb/> sir you will give place to in the Occident<lb/> I am aware that its adaptation is its only<lb/> merit therefore shall not doubt your<lb/> judgment a kindness if you decline it<lb/>  Hoping soon to see you in health and happiness<lb/> and with regard your friend <persName role="author">L B Hart</persName></p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>Should you publish&#44; do not affix aught<lb/> but <persName>L</persName> or if you choose<lb/> <persName>Marianne</persName></p>
			<pb n="4"/>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee></p>
				<p>Editor of the Occident</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>371 Walnut below 13th</placeName></p>
